<section xml:id="sec-vectors-in-Rn" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>

<p>
  Vectors in <m>\R^n</m> are very similar to vectors in the plane, except they have <m>n</m> components 
  instead of 2.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-vectors-in-Rn">
  <title>Vectors in <m>\R^n</m></title>
  <statement>
  <p>
  A <term>vector</term> <m>\vect{a}</m> in <m>\R^n</m> is an expression of the form
  <me>
  \vect{a} =
  \begin{bmatrix}
    a_1 \\ a_2\\ \vdots\\ a_n
  \end{bmatrix}
  ,
  </me>
  or <m>\vect{a} = [a_1, a_2, \dots, a_n]</m> to save space, with components <m>a_1, \dots, a_n \in \R</m>.
  </p>
  </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
  The definition of vector addition and scaling in <m>\R^n</m> is component-wise, like in 
  <m>\R^2</m>. Let <m>c\in \R</m> be a scalar, and 
  <m>\vect{a} = [a_1, a_2, \dots, a_n], \vect{b} = [b_1, b_2, \dots, b_n] \in \R^n</m> be vectors. 
  Then we define the <term>sum</term>
  <me>
  \vect{a} + \vect{b} = [a_1 + b_1, a_2 + b_2, \dots, a_n+b_n]
  </me>
  and the <term>scalar multiple</term>
  <me>
  c\vect{a} = [ca_1, ca_2, \dots, ca_n]
  </me>.
  </p>
  
  <p>
  The <term>zero vector</term> in <m>\R^n</m> is the vector
  <me>
  \vect{0} = [0, 0, \dots, 0]
  </me>
  having <m>n</m> components which are all zero.
  </p>

  <p>
  A vector in <m>\R^n</m> can still be interpreted as a directed line segment in <m>n</m>-dimensional space. 
  In <m>\R^3</m>, we can still draw vectors, add vectors tip to tail, and interpret scaling as scaling in 
  <m>3</m>-dimensional space. See <xref ref="fig-vecR3"/> for how to plot a vector in <m>\R^3</m> using its 
  components. In <m>\R^n</m> for <m>n\ge 4</m>, we can't draw vectors. However, our algebraic methods developed 
  for <m>\R^2</m> still work for <m>\R^n</m>, without any issues.
  </p>

