  <remark xml:id="rem-vecs-and-reals">
  <p>
  We can view vectors in <m>\R^1</m> as real numbers: for <m>[t] \in \R^1</m>, we consider this the same as <m>t \in \R</m>. 
  For example, we view the vector <m>[2]</m> as the number 2.
  </p>
  </remark>
  
  <example xml:id="ex-basic-vec-algebra">
  <statement>
  <p>
  In <m>\R^5</m>, let <m>\vect{a} = [1, 0, 2, 3, 1]</m> and <m>\vect{b} = [2, 1, 0, 1, 4]</m>. Then
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vect{a} + \vect{b} \amp  = [1+2, 0+1, 2+0, 3+1, 1+4] \\
  \amp  = [3, 1, 2, 4, 5],          \\
  \vect{a} - \vect{b} \amp  = [1-2, 0-1, 2-0, 3-1, 1-4] \\
  \amp  = [-1, -1, 2, 2, -3],       \\
  2\vect{a}           \amp  = [2, 0, 4, 6, 2].
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>
  </statement>
  </example>
  
  <p>
  The following fundamental properties of vectors in <m>\R^n</m> describes how addition, scaling, negation, 
  and the zero vector interact. We will call this a `Theorem', which is a name in mathematics for a fact or 
  result, usually an important one.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-vec-prop">
  <statement>
  <p>Let <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v}, \vect{w} \in \R^n</m> and <m>c, d \in \R</m>. Then
  <ol>
  <li>
  <p><m>\vect{u} + \vect{v} = \vect{v} + \vect{u}\quad</m> (commutativity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>(\vect{u} + \vect{v}) + \vect{w} = \vect{u} + (\vect{v}+ \vect{w})\quad</m> (associativity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>\vect{u} + \vect{0} = \vect{u}</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>\vect{u} + (-\vect{u}) = \vect{0}</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>c(\vect{u} + \vect{v}) = c\vect{u} + c\vect{v}\quad</m> (distributivity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>(c+d)\vect{u} = c\vect{u} + d\vect{u}\quad</m> (distributivity)
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>c(d\vect{u}) = (cd)\vect{u}</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p><m>1\vect{u} = \vect{u}</m>.</p>
  </li>
  </ol></p>
  </statement>
  </theorem>
  
  <p>
  Properties 5 and 6 are both known as distributivity. Associativity (Property 2) allows us to write sums of 
  several vectors
  <me>
  \vect{u} + \vect{v} + \vect{w}
  </me>
  without using any brackets, because no matter what order the sums are performed in, the resulting vector 
  will be same.
  </p>
  
  <p>
  Theorems are closely related to `proofs', which is a mathematical demonstration of why the fact is true. 
  We will prove Properties 3-6 to give an indication of how to do it. The proof of the remaining properties 
  will be left as an exercise.
  </p>
  
  <proof>
  <p>
  Let <m>\vect{u} = [u_1, u_2, \dots, u_n]</m> and <m>\vect{v} = [v_1, v_2, \dots, v_n]</m>. Then Property 3 is 
  proved by
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \vect{u} + \vect{0} \amp  = [u_1, u_2, \dots, u_n] + [0, 0, \dots, 0] \\
  \amp  = [u_1 + 0, u_2 + 0, \dots, u_n + 0]         \\
  \amp  = \vect{u}
  </mrow>
  </md>,
  Property 4 holds since
  <me>
  \vect{u} + (-\vect{u}) = [u_1 - u_1, \dots, u_n - u_n] = \vect{0},
  </me>
  and Property 5 holds since
  <md>
  <mrow>
  c(\vect{u} + \vect{v})
  \amp  = c([u_1 + v_1, u_2 + v_2, \dots, u_n + v_n])   \\
  \amp  = [cu_1 +cv_1, cu_2 + cv_2, \dots, cu_n + cv_n] \\
  \amp  = c\vect{u} + c\vect{v}
  </mrow>
  </md>.</p>
  <p>Finally, the following calculation
  <md>
  <mrow>
  (c+d)\vect{u} \amp  = (c+d)[u_1, u_2, \dots, u_n]                    \\
  \amp  = [(c+d)u_1, (c+d)u_2, \dots, (c+d)u_n]          \\
  \amp  = [cu_1 + du_1, cu_2 + du_2, \dots, cu_n + du_n] \\
  \amp  = c\vect{u} + d\vect{u}
  </mrow>
  </md>.
  proves Property 6.</p>
  </proof>
  
  <p>
  We can use these properties to simplify vector expressions.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-algebraic-props">
  <statement>
  <p>
  Let <m>\vect{a}, \vect{b} \in \R^n</m>. The expression 
  <m>3(2\vect{a} - \vect{b}) + (\vect{a} - 3\vect{b})</m> is simplified by
  <md>
  <mrow>
  \amp 3(2\vect{a} - \vect{b}) + (\vect{a} - 3\vect{b}) \\
  \amp\quad = 3(2\vect{a} + (-1)\vect{b}) + (\vect{a}+(-1)3\vect{b})   \quad\text{(definition of subtraction)}             \\
  \amp\quad  = [3(2\vect{a}) + 3(-1\vect{b})] + (\vect{a}+(-1)3\vect{b}) \quad\text{(distributivity)}                        \\
  \amp\quad  =[6\vect{a}+(-3\vect{b})] + (\vect{a} + (-3)\vect{b})       \quad\text{(Property 7)}                            \\
  \amp\quad  = 6\vect{a} + \vect{a} + (-3)\vect{b} + (-3)\vect{b}        \quad\text{(associativity and commutativity)}       \\
  \amp\quad  = (6+1)\vect{a} + ((-3)+(-3))\vect{b}                       \quad\text{(Property 8, distributivity)}            \\
  \amp\quad  = 7\vect{a} + (-6)\vect{b}                                  \quad\text{(addition in }\R\text{)}                      \\
  \amp\quad  = 7\vect{a} - 6\vect{b}.                                    \quad\text{(Property 7, definition of subtraction)}
  </mrow>
  </md>
  </p>
  </statement>
  </example>
  
  <p>
  We went through this example in detail to show how all the properties are applied. But in practice 
  <xref ref="thm-vec-prop"/> means that we can simplify vector algebra intuitively, using similar rules to 
  algebra with numbers. So we can combine most of the steps to do it faster, for example
  <me>
  3(2\vect{a} - \vect{b}) + (\vect{a} - 3\vect{b}) = 6\vect{a} - 3\vect{b} + \vect{a} - 3\vect{b} = 7\vect{a} - 6 \vect{b}
  </me>.
  </p>
  
  <p>
  So far, we know how to add and scale vectors. We will give a name to what happens when we combine addition 
  with scaling.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-lincomb">
  <statement>
  <p>
  A vector <m>\vect{v}\in \R^n</m> is a <term>linear combination</term> of vectors 
  <m>\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k</m> if there are scalars <m>c_1, c_2, \dots, c_k \in \R</m> 
  such that
  <me>
  \vect{v} = c_1\vect{v}_1 + c_2\vect{v}_2 + \dots + c_k\vect{v}_k
  </me>.
  </p>
  
  <p>
  The scalars <m>c_1, c_2, \dots, c_k</m> are called the <term>coefficients</term> of the linear combination.
  </p>
  </statement>
  </definition>

  <example xml:id="ex-lincomb">
  <statement>
  <p>
  Write <m>\vect{u} = [2, 2]</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vect{v} = [-1, 1]</m> and 
  <m>\vect{w} = [0, 4]</m>. Let <m>\vect{u} = c_1\vect{v} + c_2\vect{w}</m>, i.e\
  <me>
    [2, 2] = c_1[-1, 1] + c_2[0, 4]
  </me>.
  </p>

  <p>
  Comparing components gives <me>
  \begin{aligned}
    2 \amp  = -c_1       \\
    2 \amp  = c_1 + 4c_2. \\
  \end{aligned}
  </me>
  so <m>c_1 = -2, c_2 = \frac{1}{4}(2-c_1) = 1</m>. Thus <m>\vect{u} = -2\vect{v} + \vect{w}</m>. 
  See <xref ref="fig-lincomb-ex"/>.
  </p>

