  </figure>
  </statement>
  </example>
  
  <example xml:id="ex-non-lc">
  <statement>
  <p>
  Is it possible to write <m>\vect{u} = [2, 2]</m> as a linear combination of <m>\vect{v} = [-1, 1]</m> and 
  <m>\vect{x} = [3, -3]</m>?
  </p>
  
  <p>
  Suppose we try to write <m>\vect{u} = c_1\vect{v} + c_2\vect{x}</m>, so
    <me>
    [2, 2] = c_1[-1, 1] + c_2[3, -3]
  </me>.
  </p>
  
  <p>
  Comparing coefficients gives
  <me>
 \begin{aligned}
    2 \amp  = -c_1 + 3c_2 \\
    2 \amp  = c_1 - 3c_2.  \\
  \end{aligned}
  </me>
  </p>
  
  <p>
  Adding these equations gives <m>4=0</m>, which is a contradiction. Therefore <m>\vect{u}</m> cannot be 
  written as a linear combination of <m>\vect{v}</m> and <m>\vect{x}</m>. This is also shown 
  in <xref ref="fig-lincomb-nonex"/>: since <m>\vect{u}</m> does not lie on the dashed line, it 
  cannot be a linear combination of <m>\vect{v}</m> and <m>\vect{x}</m>.
  </p>

